  \starttitle[title={Glossary}]
    \startconcept{Beast of Failure:}
      An imaginary merciless and insatiable creature
      that devours most new product ideas and bites and slashes those who
      pursue those ideas without first validating them.
    \stopconcept

    \startconcept{Data beats opinions:}
      A key rule you need to internalize and
      practice with no exceptions if you want to improve your odds for market
      success. Don't base your product decisions on opinions. Base them on
      market data, and not just any old data or other people's data (see
      OPD)---but your own (see YODA).
    \stopconcept

    \startconcept{DTD (Distance to Data):}
      A metric to help you quantify and minimize
      how far you have to go to collect your market data.
    \stopconcept

    \startconcept{\textdollar{}TD (Dollars to Data):}
      A metric to help you quantify and minimize
      how much it will cost to collect your market data.
    \stopconcept

    \startconcept{expert opinions:}
      {\em See} opinions.
    \stopconcept

    \startconcept{Failure is not an option:}
      An inspiring but wrong and often harmful
      phrase and belief suitable for Hollywood movies but ill suited for most
      business ventures. Use it only if you are writing dialogue for an action
      flick with Arnold Schwarzenegger.
    \stopconcept

    \startconcept{false negative:}
      An idea that is mocked and knocked in Thoughtland but, when competently
      executed and brought to market, turns out to be a success.
    \stopconcept

    \startconcept{false positive:}
      An idea that sounds great in Thoughtland, is
      competently executed and brought to market, and fails miserably. Most
      market failures are false positives.
    \stopconcept

    \startconcept{HTD (Hours to Data):}
      A metric to help you quantify and minimize
      how long it will take to collect your market data.
    \stopconcept

    \startconcept{hypozooming:}
      The process of taking an XYZ Hypothesis and \quotation{zooming}
      it in with regard to scope, space, and time to derive a set of smaller
      related xyz hypotheses that can be tested locally, quickly, and
      inexpensively. For example, the xyz hypothesis for Second-Day Sushi: \quotation{At
      least 20\textpercent{} of students buying packaged sushi at Coupa Caf
      today at lunch will choose Second-Day Sushi if it's half the price of
      regular packaged sushi.} The principle is that if the XYZ Hypothesis is
      true, then the easily testable hypozoomed xyz hypotheses derived from it
      will reflect that.
    \stopconcept

    \startconcept{If there's a market, there's a way:}
      An important reminder that if
      there's enough market interest in an idea for a product, you (or someone
      else) will usually be able to find a way around whatever engineering,
      financial, legal, or other obstacles currently stand between the idea
      and its realization. If an idea is The Right It, one way or another it
      will usually find its way to market.
    \stopconcept

    \startconcept{If there's no market, there's no way:}
      If there is no market
      interest in an idea, no amount of brilliant design, amazing engineering,
      superior reliability, or marketing fireworks will help the idea succeed.
    \stopconcept

    \startconcept{If we build it, they will come:}
      An overly optimistic, ill-founded sentiment not
      suitable for business ventures, because they {\em won't} come, unless
      you are building The Right It. However, by transposing two words and
      adding a question mark, you get the critical question you should ask
      before building anything: \quotation{If we build it, will they come?} That's the
      key question this book helps you answer.
    \stopconcept

    \startconcept{Law of Market Failure:}
      \quotation{Most new products will fail in the market,
      even if competently executed}; the stubborn hard fact that most new
      product ideas are destined to fail and that competent execution of an
      idea cannot save it from failure.
    \stopconcept

    \startconcept{market failure:}
      When the actual market result from an investment
      in a new product is less than or the opposite of the expected result.
    \stopconcept

    \startconcept{market success:}
      When the actual market result from an investment
      in a new product meets or exceeds the expected result.
    \stopconcept

    \startconcept{MEH (Market Engagement Hypothesis):}
      A high-level description that
      combines the fundamental premise behind a new product idea with a vision
      of how the target market will engage with it. For example, the MEH for
      Second-Day Sushi: \quotation{A lot of people who want to eat healthy and who like
      sushi can't afford to eat it regularly, because sushi tends to be quite
      expensive. If we can find a way to make sushi as affordable as other
      fast food, a lot of fast-food patrons will choose sushi over less
      healthy alternatives.}
    \stopconcept

    \startconcept{OPD (Other People's Data):}
      Market data collected by other people
      at other times, in other places, with other methods, using other
      filters, and for other purposes. Technically, OPD is data, but
      since it's not {\em
      your} data, it can be as dangerous and as misleading as opinions. OPD is
      no substitute for YODA ({\em see} YODA), and given that OPD is neither
      necessary nor sufficient for evaluating your ideas, it's best to not
      waste time seeking it.
    \stopconcept

    \startconcept{opinions:}
      Subjective, biased, and often baseless judgments about
      an idea's prospects for success. In the quest for The Right It, opinions
      are worse than useless---they are downright dangerous and misleading.
    \stopconcept

    \startconcept{pretotype:}
      A specific artifact or technique used in pretotyping.
      Some pretotypes are the Mechanical Turk, the Pinocchio, the Fake Door,
      the Facade, the YouTube, the One-Night Stand, the Infiltrator, and the
      Relabel.
    \stopconcept

    \startconcept{pretotyping:}
      Using a group of tools and techniques to collect
      fresh, reliable, and relevant market data ({\em see} YODA) about an idea
      for a new product as quickly and as inexpensively as possible. The goal
      of pretotyping is to help you {\em make sure that you are building The
      Right It before you build It right.}
    \stopconcept

    \startconcept{Say it with numbers:}
      A reminder to quantify whenever possible. A
      number, even if it's just an educated guess at the time, is more
      informative and useful than some fuzzy, vague term. For example, instead
      of \quotation{Our widget will be inexpensive,} say, \quotation{Our widget will cost \textdollar{}10,}
      or \quotation{Our widget will cost 40\textpercent{} less than the
      competition's.}
    \stopconcept

    \startconcept{skin in the game:}
      Something {\em of value} given to you by the
      market as evidence of interest in your idea. The simplest form of skin
      in the game is money (\fsp{e.g.}, a paid preorder or a deposit), but it could
      also be someone's time, information, reputation, and so on.
    \stopconcept

    \startconcept{Skin-in-the-Game Caliper:}
      A tool to help you quantify and calibrate skin in the game,
      necessary because not all skin in the game is created equal. For
      example, a \textdollar{}1,000 preorder for a product should count more than a \textdollar{}100
      deposit for the same product, and a commitment to attend a one-hour
      presentation should count more than, say, an email address.
    \stopconcept

    \startconcept{Thoughtland:}
      An imaginary place where ideas for new products hang
      around collecting solicited and unsolicited opinions. Like visits to Las
      Vegas, visits to Thoughtland are best kept short: most of what happens
      in Thoughtland should stay in Thoughtland.
    \stopconcept

    \startconcept{The Right It:}
      An idea for a new product (or service, company,
      initiative, \fsp{etc.}) that, {\em if} competently executed, will succeed in
      the market. The Right It is like Kryptonite to the Beast of Failure.
    \stopconcept

    \startconcept{The Wrong It:}
      An idea for a new product (or service, company,
      initiative, \fsp{etc.}) that, {\em even if} competently executed, will fail in
      the market. The Wrong It is like catnip to the Beast of Failure.
    \stopconcept

    \startconcept{TRI Meter (The Right It Meter):}
      A tool for mapping and visualizing
      the results of pretotyping experiments to help determine how likely it
      is that an idea is The Right It.
    \stopconcept

    \startconcept{XYZ Hypothesis:}
      What you get when you apply \quotation{say it with numbers}
      to the Market Engagement Hypothesis. The basic form for the XYZ
      Hypothesis is: \quotation{At least X\textpercent{} of Y will Z,} where
      X\textpercent{} represents a percentage of your target market, Y, and
      Z represents how that percentage of the market will engage with your new
      product idea. For example, the XYZ Hypothesis for Second-Day Sushi: \quotation{At
      least 20\textpercent{} of packaged-sushi eaters will try Second-Day
      Sushi if it's half the price of regular packaged sushi.}
    \stopconcept

    \startconcept{xyz hypothesis:}
      A small, specific,
      easily and quickly testable hypothesis that is derived from, and
      consistent with, a broader XYZ Hypothesis. For example, a possible xyz
      hypothesis for Second-Day Sushi is: \quotation{At least 20\textpercent{} of
      students buying packaged sushi at Coupa Caf today at lunch will choose
      Second-Day Sushi if it's half the price of regular packaged sushi.} The
      process of going from a broad XYZ Hypothesis to one or more xyz
      hypotheses is called {\em hypozooming.}
    \stopconcept

    \startconcept{YODA (Your Own DAta):}
      Data about {\em your own} product idea,
      collected firsthand by {\em you and your own team}, by running
      experiments {\em you} designed to validate {\em your own} market
      hypotheses. To qualify as such, YODA must come with skin in the game
      ({\em see} skin in the game). Unlike OPD, YODA is both necessary and
      sufficient for evaluating your idea.
    \stopconcept
